context: <a4_0><b5_0>Tibet<b5_0/><a4_0/> (i/tᵻˈbɛt/; Wylie: Bod, pronounced [pʰø̀ʔ]; Chinese: 西藏; <b9_0>pinyin<b9_0/>: Xīzàng) is a region on the Tibetan Plateau in <a1_0>Asia<a1_0/>. It is the traditional homeland of the Tibetan people as well as some other ethnic groups such as <b6_0>Monpa, Qiang and Lhoba peoples<b6_0/> and is now also inhabited by considerable numbers of Han Chinese and Hui people. <b7_0>Tibet<b7_0/> is the highest region on Earth, with an average elevation of 4,900 metres (<a2_0>16,000<a2_0/> ft). The highest elevation in Tibet is <a0_0><b8_0>Mount Everest<b8_0/><a0_0/>, earth's highest mountain rising 8,848 m (<a3_0>29,029<a3_0/> ft) above sea level.
